I try to understand people. I like understanding people. I like to know why they are doing things or what motivates them. I'm super interested in reading people through body language, handwriting analysis and things like that. But maybe the quickest and most helpful way I've come across to understand people at a glance is through Carol Tuttles' interesting interpretation of the four main personalities. She labels them by their life mission. 1- idea makers, 2- planners, 3- doers, & 4- refiners. Obviously people are not so easily categorized and everybody has a little bit of everything inside them. But, generally speaking, people can fit into one of these categories with one being main and another a secondary. Carol Tuttle focuses now it seems on how to dress to release your inner personal mission, which is always fun. But one of her books has really helped me especially understand my children and how to talk to them, really to them, motivate them to do what needs doing (like chores). Ha ha, 1s like playing and changing up the fun so instead of just asking my daughter to help me sweep the floor before my meeting, I asked if she could hover board clean with me and we would both be on wheels 😂 she had a blast and didn't complain once! I'm embarrassed by that huge pile of popcorn and dirt (🤪) - kids and dogs, what can I say? But I am so proud of her for sweeping it all up herself. I didn't really contribute much with the sweeping until after I took this video. I'm pretty sure she's predominately a 1, but she could be mostly a 4? I don't know. It's hard to tell, she switches so quickly between the two! It's either/or for her. But the info is in The Child Whisperer by Carol Tuttle and it will change your parenting - and the way you see people - forever. Check her out and if you know her, ask if Daisy is predominantly a 1 or a 4 😂 @caroltuttle

The rocky times in life happen despite our great efforts to avoid them. As long as we keep walking down our path, we will be challenged—physically, emotionally, mentally, and spiritually. It is difficult to continue on a straight course along our path, partly because the rough patches seem unbearable and partly because off the trail seems so much more enticing. Off the trail seems easier. Better. Nicer. Smoother.

But as smooth as off the trail seems and as tempted as we are to relieve ourselves of the difficulties of our path, we can’t go near it. We must remain on our path because looming dangerously close to the edge of our path is not-soft sand to rest our feet but rather gaps between the rocks. And if we fall into these gaps, something worse than physical damage will occur.
.
.
.

As difficult as it is to imagine, it’s true. I can’t feel my legs, even if you stab them. Being numb to the world around me is weird. I mean, I spent twenty-two years being able to feel everything normally, and now I’m unable to feel most of my body. When I let my feet hang off my wheelchair bar and down to the grass, I crave the feeling of the grassy tickle, but it won’t come for me.
 
I’m unsure if I’ll ever be able to get used to not feeling with my physical senses.
But as strange and difficult as it is to not feel my physical world, it is nothing compared to what happens when Satan pulls us into the surrounding gaps. When we become spiritually paralyzed, our feelings become muted—we can no longer feel the sweet peace of the Spirit or the loving arms of the Savior. We block out the soul-tickling sensations we get when we receive divine guidance and inspiration. When we allow ourselves to fall into the gaps that surround the path, we choose to become spiritually numb.

Making long lists of things we are grateful for can be good, and it will help us through extremely rough patches along the trail. However, expressing our gratitude only in this way is the equivalent of eating a week’s worth of food at once. Time-wise, it makes sense; I mean, we have to eat that much anyway, so why not just do it all at once and get it over with? But cramming all our food in will make us feel sick for one day (maybe two . . .) and hungry for all the others. And just like our food, gratitude is not a weekly or biweekly or “in-times-of-need,” all-at-once activity. Creating lengthy lists of our blessings, while fun, will take a lot of time out of our already busy days and will soon wear us out. If we feel like we should create a long list of things we’re grateful for, we’ve likely been gratitude starved.

A healthy way to express gratitude to our Heavenly Father is consistently throughout the day. We will feel “full” as we express gratitude in our morning prayers, to our family, while driving our car, on our bikes, in our gardens, and to our neighbors. As we are constantly grateful, we will rarely feel hungry for the Spirit; He will fill us. Through hard times, though, we may be a little hungrier for the Spirit, and making a long gratitude list “snack” will fill us back up.

We are sons and daughters of our Heavenly Father. He and His Son, Jesus Christ, are keenly aware of where we are and what we are doing. They knew us before we came to earth, and They know us now. With so many people in the world, I often wonder how my little problems and struggles could rank very high on any divine “importance scale,” but Heavenly Father has shown me again and again that I matter. I love how author C. S. Lewis describes our personal relationship with the Lord: “He has infinite attention to spare for each one of us. He does not have to deal with us in the mass. You are as much alone with Him as if you were the only being He had ever created.”

My dad's birthday would have been this week. He would have been 79 years old. He passed away in May and I am a little sad, but a lot happy for him. 

He loved gardening, baseball, and the Tennessee Volunteers. I think the reason the Vols did so well this year was because he was their orange angel helping them along. My mom said he for sure was watching, but I'm pretty sure he was on the field playing. I think those angels really know how to help. 

I'm not sure what angels watch out for me, but one of them spoke to me the last time I saw my dad alive. We had visited him as a family and videoed one of my YouTube videos of him. 

We stayed and chatted for a while and when we left, eveeryone gave hugs as we always did. But then I heard an angel whisper and tell me to give my dad a kiss. That's not our normal, so it was awkward, but I leaned over and kissed his cheek. 

A lot happened after that video, my baby came a couple months early and I was rushing to the hospital every day for 40 days to see her as she grew up for the first little while in the NICU. Once we brought her home, I waited two weeks before I felt comfortable driving with her in the carseat because her oxygen levels kept dropping when she was in it. But after two weeks I felt more comfortable and we planned to go see my dad on Sunday. 

But he died on Saturday. 

I was too late. 

His death came as a surprise to me and all who knew him, but I guess the angels knew. And the angels helped me have no regrets because I really had, awkwardly, kissed him goodbye. 

It's a brand new year and I hope this is the year you can hear the angels speaking to you to guide you along the way and do what (maybe awkwardly) needs doing so you can feel happy even when things might get a little sad.

Football is a big part of our home. My husband loves to watch sports and football is a big deal to him. When we were first married, I was surprised that there were football games on all the time. It was like you didn't care which team was playing! And he didn't. Not always anyway. When he turned to the TV to yet another game, I drew the breath to make a comment, it wasn't going to be a rude comment, just a little sarcastic maybe. I was just going to say something like, " Oh good, another game…" but I heard words in my heart saying that the Spirit would be in my home if football is in my home. I have ever since pondered the strangeness of that message. But I have never complained about football games being on. One of the games that was on recently was the Bills vs. the Bengals. My husband and I saw the scary scenes unfolding with Damar Hamlin and we couldn't take our eyes away from what happened next, even though it happened next was a lot of waiting and waiting. Thousands and thousands of people just waiting to hear if he was okay. I took a picture of this beautiful scene where the players from the two opposing teams came together and knelt on the ground and united in prayer to one God. The excitement of the game, the excitement for the outcome, the excitement in general was paused as thousands of people present, and who knows how many watching from homes, awoke to the importance of life and united together to pray to one God for one person. I'm very happy the Damar Hamlin is going to be ok and very happy that he was willing to "take one for the team" as he helped to unite us all. ❤️

People sometimes want to wait until the trial ends before they let themselves feel happy –as if feeling happy during a trial would somehow give the trial permission to stay! We don't have to wait until a trial leaves. Because, let's face it, some trials are sticking around way longer than we'd like them to. And do we really believe that happy feelings can only come when our life is easy? 

No! 

No matter what is happening, or not happening, you can feel happy. Feeling happy is a skill and we have to work hard (way hard sometimes) to muster those feelings. We have to do the things that bring happiness. My short list is service, songs, and sleep. I just noticed those all start with S.  But my go-to, never-fail, tried-and-true technique is expressing gratitude. What do you do for a quick emotional pick-me-up?

I think we all have a tendency to compare. 

If we're on social media...which, I suspect, you are...you can't help but see the photoshopped, filtered videos and pictures of beautiful people with beautiful lives. 

And then you look up from your phone and see something less than beautiful. Maybe even something messy and unwanted. 

I get it. I do it, too. 

But there's something valuable in our unwanted mess. 

It's in our trials that we gain strength from enduring and confidence in overcoming. Trials even provide purpose as they open the doors of opportunity that we wouldn't otherwise be able to open. If we squared our shoulders and let ourselves learn from our trials and walk through those doors of opportunity, we will discover our unique purpose and we will fulfill our missions in this life. 

What trials have you overcome...or are you overcoming... that have provided opportunities for you to accomplish your purposes in life?

In the quiet, I looked at my lifeless, paralyzed legs. I spoke aloud, "Are you done yet? Really, are you done? Because I want to stand. I want to dance! Are you done being paralyzed so I can do those things?" To my surprise, my legs spoke back. "You think YOU want to stand? You think YOU want to dance? We are doing this for YOU. We are waiting for YOU. We have put standing and dancing off so you can accomplish the things that you need to accomplish. So don't let us down." 

Our bodies are working hard, day and night, to help us do what we got to do in this life. Let's treat them kindly. Eat what we need to eat. Don't eat what we shouldn't eat. Exercise. Some things we can't fix, but we can give our bodies every reason to know how much we love them and appreciate their patience, love, a nd help in accomplishing our missions in this life.

Peace is the exclusive right of the Holy Ghost. The adversary can't duplicate peace. We can't manufacture it ourselves. No one else, no friend,  no speaker, no no one, can give us peace. We can only feel it when we feel the Holy Ghost. So, if you think about it, if you have the Holy Ghost with you 24/7, you can feel peace 24/7. No matter what is crashing around you. After I was paralyzed, I was surprised by how calm and peaceful I felt as I laid at the bottom of a cliff. We don't need peaceful situations to bring peace. We can have peace anywhere when we feel the presence of the Holy Ghost.

And because I know this, I can do anything. When was the last time you felt God's love for you? 

I felt it the other day. I prayed that my dad, who passed away last year, would have permission to come see me, to just be able to send me a message that he was thinking about me. 

Within a matter of hours I was sitting at my dining room table, just quiet, when all the sudden I felt my dad sitting right across from me. 

I reached out my hand and I have no doubt that my dad reached out his, too. I cried. He didn't say anything. 

He didn't tell me or show me anything, heck, I didn't even see him. But just knowing my earthly father cares  about me and came because I asked my Heavenly Father to send him lets me know that both love me.

I’m sure this comes as no surprise to hear that fcusing on the bad brings the bad into focus. 

Focusing on what is going right, even if it’s small, will keep the focus on what is happy and you’ll feel happy.
 
I learned this lesson when I was in the Respiratory ICU of the hospital after I was paralyzed. I was crying because I was alone, tied to the bed (they thought I also had brain damage so they tied my arms to the metal sides of the bed), with tubes coming out from everywhere - my elbow pits, my nose, my mouth, my lungs, my upper arms even. I had the metal halo screwed into my head. I was on a ventilator. And I was crying.

I didn’t know what to do so I opened my eyes and prayed for love for the ceiling, the window, the light switch, the TV... and I felt better. So much better that I was crying. But this time, I was crying because I was so happy. 

I had gone from being so sad - to the point of tears - to being so happy - to the point of tears - simply by loving the things in my hospital room. 

Focus on the good and the good will come into focus.

I attribute my personal emotional healing to many things. Service. Gratitude. Journaling.
Being happy is something I work hard at and there are skills that we can hone to help us be happy.
I recently discovered something else to which I can give credit for helping me with a good attitude and optimistic life: Speaking.
I began speaking right out of the hospital. I was invited to speak at a nurse’s convention. I had never given a talk from a stage and I didn’t know what to do when the audience suddenly applauded in the middle of my speech, so I left the stage! Now I love intermittent applause.
From that speech, I was invited to speak again, then again. That is how my career began. Practice makes perf...well, better than I began anyway. I don’t claim to be a great speaker, but the stories I share are true and I feel like my life is one everyone can relate to because we all feel disabled at times.
I walked for 22 years before I was paralyzed and I know that you don’t have to be in a wheelchair to feel like life is too hard to stand. I feel happy to share what I know about happiness with audiences.
What I didn’t know was that all of my sharing was actually helping me.
My friend and his family went through a very difficult trial and he found himself immediately afterwards on a Hawaiian vacation. He didn’t want to go, but it was already booked and paid for.
On a scuba excursion, he felt sick and climbed back on the boat. He sat by to two psychiatrists. My friend told them about his family’s awful experience. They told him that it was good he was there, the best thing to do after a life-changing trial is to get away for a vacation.
The next step, they said, is to speak about their experience. They told him that speaking and sharing will help him and his family.
I hadn’t realized how speaking has not just been a mission I am on to share good messages, but has been a way for me to organize my thoughts and when I help others laugh and learn through my experiences, I am doing the same.
Many people share with me that they feel called to speak or write a book about what they have been through. I would encourage all to do this! I have found it healing and I know you will, too!

Sometimes God doesn’t remove trials, but God is always ready to provide assistance when we ask for help enduring what we have to endure and doing what we need to do – in the midst of the trials God isn’t removing.

I don’t want to be paralyzed. It would be great if God would answer my prayer and heal me. But He hasn’t (yet) so I keep praying for healing AND for help enduring the trial.

I was rolling down a deserted street to a class. I couldn’t use the sidewalks because the tree roots had broken through the concrete. And the road was high in the middle and sloped downward toward each sidewalk at a steep angle.

Each sidewalk had a deep gutter. Like very deep.

No way was I going to roll my little wheelchair self near those gutters so I was midway in the road lane, not quite to the middle where it wouldn’t have had such a harsh slope.

I kept pushing my wheelchair, it was difficult to maintain a straight course because of the pull toward the gutter.

I didn’t realize that the road started to go downhill. And I was picking up speed. So much speed that I was soon rolling down the hill, unable to control my wheels or my wheelchair or myself at all!

And my wheelchair was veering toward the gutter.

The GUTTER.

For sure I was going to get hurt, but just the emotional blow of landing in a gutter was insult to injury.

I cried out in prayer, “Help me!”

I felt someone grab the handles of my wheelchair. They slowed me down and I was able to get control. I looked around and there was no one to be seen.

God knew I was on my way to that class. He knew I couldn’t take the sidewalk and I was on the road. He knew the road went downhill and He knew I had picked up speed. He knew I had lost control and He knew I was heading toward the gutter.

But He didn’t step in until I asked Him to.

We sometimes underestimate prayer because we feel our prayers aren’t being answered.

And they aren’t, at least they aren’t always answered in the ways that we hope. But when we combine faith to accept the trials God sends us with the faith to ask for help to endure them and live our life in spite of them, we’ll discover miracles in our lives that keep us away from the paralyzing gutters.

I want to be happy.

It’d be nice to be healed and walking, but if I have to be paralyzed, then I will settle for just being happy while I’m here.

Sometimes people think they can’t have both. 

That being happy is something that happens in between trials.

But this is incorrect. Happiness can - and must - happen while trials are raging.

Why should we wait for happiness?

Why should we delay it?

Happiness is completely possible with a little effort. 

“What can I do?” you might ask. 

Well, it’s pretty dang simple, really. I mean, it takes effort, but the answer is not complicated.

Sing a happy song.

List things you’re grateful for. 

Pray. Go on, do it. 

Write in a journal. 

These things are small things and they will, without changing much, change everything.

I am a C-7 quadriplegic. Sometimes doctors refer to the injury I have as tetriplegia or say I am a tetraplegic. In general, you could say I have a spinal cord injury. I fell off a cliff when I was 22 and I broke my neck. I broke four of the cervical bones, known as C-3, C-4, C-5, and C-6. C-5 was crushed completely and I have a donor's bone. That's where my level of injury is, but the functionality drops two levels so that's why I'm considered a C-7 quad. No one knows why, maybe you can become a doctor and figure it out! While you're at it, maybe you can develop a cure, too! That'll be an awesome day🥰 but for now, I'll do the best I can on this side of walking with the abilities I have. My biceps, triceps, and wrist extension all work, which is awesome. My fingers don't move, but I can feel them mostly, the only ones I can't feel are my pinkies. So that pretty much sums up what I do and don't have. I might be paralyzed, but really, am I all that paralyzed? #notsoparalyzed

I think I have been blessed with a particularly vivid imagination. 

I can imagine pretty much anything and I didn’t know that it wasn’t just a normal thing to be able to do until my husband asked if I could really, truly look at our white shower curtain and change its color, willy nilly. Like could I just look at it, with my eyes open, and see it be pink? Or black even? 

I looked at my husband because I thought it was the strangest question. I told him that I could imagine our shower curtain being made out of live monkeys each with a different outfit on. That’s when I learned that not everyone could do that. 

Let me know how imaginative you are in the comments, I’d really love to know. 

But I do attribute my vivid imagination to my ability to accomplish goals. Because once I see my goal taking shape, I can’t unsee it. I can only see my goal, even if I am looking at the broken pieces of a solid attempt. I try again and again until I reach my goal and see for reals what I’ve been seeing all along. 

A spiritual creation is needed before a physical manifestation can happen. 

We mustn’t discount the planning and dreaming process, the creation of the end result is what will drive us on to victory, no matter what level of imagination we may have.

Who we are, what we love to do, and how we see the world is not only adequate, it’s beautiful. 

We were not designed to stand out, we were designed to stand tall in who we are. For those who blend in and fit the mold, they’ve learned to hide and downplay the interesting and lovely parts about themselves. 

At least for the most part. Each of us is uniquely interesting and has so much to offer this world. 

I think we all try hard to love and accept others for who they are and what part of their journey - maybe we can offer the same courtesy to ourselves? 

Maybe we don’t have to be perfect, not yet anyway. 

Maybe we’re okay to sing in the choir, not because we’re amazing at it (yet), but because singing is part of what we love. 

Or maybe we can dance even though no one is inviting us onto dancing with the stars… maybe we don’t have to be awesome at something to feel awesome doing it. 

Let’s not only let others do what they love - we can join in, too!

My brother, Tom, has been an alcoholic for 15 years. He would fall and get hurt when he drank. Sometimes he would resurface and often he would have cuts or bruises on his face. Once, the entire left side of his face was scratched, like one full scab from forehead to chin. He must have slid his face down a concrete wall or something. I will never forget it. I felt so bad for him, he wouldn't ever admit that he had a drinking problem. I was pretty sure that he was going to die an alcoholic.

I was shocked when he told me he was sober. I have never been so happy, or so sad as that day. I was so happy because he was sober! But I was so sad because he was the worst I had ever seen him. He hardly had teeth. He had a few in the front, but no molars. And he was missing one of his front teeth. He held his head up high, but I could tell if he was embarrassed. He kept covering his mouth to speak or laugh.

Sometimes we don't get to choose the consequences of our actions. Sometimes the consequences stick. It didn't matter how sober he was, his teeth were not going to grow back. Enter @stubbsdentalutah. They transformed Tom back into Tom and helped him restart life on the other side of awful. They couldn't give him back any of the years that he drank away, but they did shine a light on the years that lay ahead.

After his all-on-x permanent teeth implant, Tom has stopped covering his mouth when he laughs. He smiles much more easily now, just like he used to. It's like meeting Tom again. He deserves the credit for taking control of his own life and making changes to restart his life.

Tom is the one who holds the pencil that writes the next chapter in his life. But Stubbs Dental has erasers. They can erase some of the consequences so Tom can restart his life and look like he used to look. Handsome. Confident. And truly beautiful. Stubbs Dental was so nice from the get-go, so talented, and so non-judgmental. They were as nice to Tom when he had no teeth as they were when he had beautiful teeth again.

Tom’s always been super funny and awesome, but now he's confident. Go say hi to him @tomhendleman and if you ever get the chance, give Stubbs Dental a high five for me!

I am a C-7 quadriplegic. Sometimes doctors refer to the injury I have as tetriplegia or say I am a tetraplegic. In general, you could say I have a spinal cord injury. I fell off a cliff when I was 22 and I broke my neck. I broke four of the cervical bones, known as C-3, C-4, C-5, and C-6. C-5 was crushed completely and I have a donor's bone. That's where my level of injury is, but the functionality drops two levels so that's why I'm considered a C-7 quad. No one knows why, maybe you can become a doctor and figure it out! While you're at it, maybe you can develop a cure, too! That'll be an awesome day🥰 but for now, I'll do the best I can on this side of walking with the abilities I have. My biceps, triceps, and wrist extension all work, which is awesome. My fingers don't move, but I can feel them mostly, the only ones I can't feel are my pinkies.
